<p>As you can see, the parties are ranked based on how probable they are to seat with one another. Note that just this listing of probabilities is probably highly political and in the time since the last election (all of a week ago), the situation has likely changed. </p><p>All of that said, I don’t really think that it is fair of a job candidate to actually <em>solve</em> the issue at an interview. I’m pretty sure that would require dynamic programming and a lot of brute force (yes, this is a political joke), but the idea is to get a list of ranked coalition options. </p><p>If you want to try it, the initial parameters are here:</p><blockquote><script src="https://gist.github.com/ayende/d275ca9a2ad6c6f16c3643c491e6ec14.js"></script></blockquote><p>And hey, we won’t get a government out of this, but hopefully we’ll get a new employee <img class="wlEmoticon wlEmoticon-smile" style="" alt="Smile" src="https://ayende.com/blog/Images/Open-Live-Writer/Giving-a-job-candidate-a-HARD-problem_10779/wlEmoticon-smile_2.png">.</p>
